A large number of studies on the relationship between smoking and certain diseases conducted in a certain region are as follows.<image 1>Based on this information, the AR% comparing smoking and non-smoking in relation to the disease are

A. 48.0
B. 48.0-25.4=22.6
C. 48.0/25.4=1.89
D. (48.0-25.4) /48.0

To determine the attributable risk percentage (AR%) comparing smoking and non-smoking in relation to the disease, we need to use the formula:

\[ \text{AR\%} = \left( \frac{\text{Incidence in exposed} - \text{Incidence in unexposed}}{\text{Incidence in exposed}} \right) \times 100 \]

Given:
- Incidence in exposed (smokers) = 48.0 per 100,000
- Incidence in unexposed (non-smokers) = 25.4 per 100,000

Plugging these values into the formula:

\[ \text{AR\%} = \left( \frac{48.0 - 25.4}{48.0} \right) \times 100 \]

\[ \text{AR\%} = \left( \frac{22.6}{48.0} \right) \times 100 \]

\[ \text{AR\%} = 0.470833333 \times 100 \]

\[ \text{AR\%} = 47.0833333 \]

So, the correct answer is:

D. (48.0-25.4) /48.0
